  "prompt": "Are there international laws against money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are several international laws and conventions designed to combat money laundering, including:\n\n1. The Financial Action Task Force (FATF) Recommendations\n- Global standard-setting body for anti-money laundering efforts\n- Provides guidelines for countries to implement\n\n2. United Nations Convention Against Transnational Organized Crime\n- Adopted in 2000\n- Requires member states to criminalize money laundering\n\n3. The Palermo Convention\n- Provides framework for international cooperation against organized crime\n- Includes provisions for preventing money laundering\n\n4. Basel Committee Guidelines\n- International banking standards for detecting and preventing money laundering\n\n5. European Union Anti-Money Laundering Directives\n- Establish uniform rules for financial institutions in EU countries\n\n6. Bank Secrecy Act (US)\n- Requires financial institutions to assist government agencies in detecting and preventing money laundering\n\nThese laws typically require financial institutions to:\n- Verify customer identities\n- Report suspicious transactions\n- Maintain transaction records\n- Implement compliance programs\n- Cooperate with law enforcement investigations\n\nMost developed countries have domestic laws implementing these international standards, creating a comprehensive global approach to preventing money laundering.",
